ts protective properties, safeguarding components against premature wear and ensuring optimal efficiency and performance throughout its service life.</p>', 'simple', '1 Item', 500, 50, 15.00, 13.20, 12.00, 0, NULL, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TO08', 0, 'in_stock', 'Indilube Synthetic Lubricant', 'Indilube Synthetic Lubricant stands at the forefront of lubrication innovation, embodying the pinnacle of performance and reliability for a myriad of mechanical applications. Crafted with precision and expertise, this lubricant harnesses cutting-edge synthetic compounds to deliver unparalleled protection and efficiency to vital machinery components. Its advanced formulation is meticulously engineered to surpass industry standards, providing exceptional lubricating properties that effectively reduce friction, diminish wear, and optimize the operational lifespan of mechanical systems.\n\nAt the heart of Indilube Synthetic Lubricant lies a meticulously curated blend of synthetic base oils and premium additives, meticulously selected to ensure optimum performance under a broad spectrum of operating conditions. From extreme temperatures to heavy loads, this lubricant maintains superior stability and consistency, delivering steadfast lubrication that safeguards equipment and maximizes performance. Its ability to resist oxidation, maintain viscosity, and withstand harsh environments ensures reliable protection and prolonged service life for critical machinery components.\n\nIndilube Synthetic Lubricant\'s versatility makes it well-suited for a diverse range of applications across various industries, including automotive, industrial, marine, and more. Whether applied to engine components, industrial machinery, or marine equipment, this lubricant excels in providing robust protection and enhancing performance in demanding operating environments. Its proven ability to endure extreme pressures, resist corrosion, and maintain lubricating properties over time ensures consistent and dependable performance, minimizing downtime and reducing maintenance costs for operators.\n\nBacked by a commitment to quality and customer satisfaction, Indilube Synthetic Lubricant is manufactured in state-of-the-art facilities with rigorous quality control measures. Trusted by professionals worldwide, it embodies excellence in lubrication technology, offering peace of mind and unmatched protection for critical machinery components in a wide range of applications. From automotive engines to industrial equipment, Indilube Synthetic Lubricant sets the standard for reliability, performance, and longevity in lubrication solutions.', 2132, 2132, NULL, 'Your order is likely to reach you within 4-6 days.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 'indilube-synthetic-lubricant', 1, 25, 1, 1, 'url', 'physical', NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, 0, 'center', 73, NULL, 'fixed', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-29 21:44:40', '2024-05-29 21:44:40'),
(379, 'Alloy Wheel Tyre', 'Alloy wheels are designed to provide a perfect fit for your car tyres, with the wheel width dictating the tyre size combinations. The wheel offset, measured in inches or millimeters, determines how much the wheel will stick out from the hub mounting surface. Correct wheel offset is crucial to avoid damage to the vehicle and ensure safe driving.', '<p style=\"text-align:start\"><span style=\"color:rgb(55, 65, 81);\"><span style=\"background-color:rgba(244, 244, 245, 0.5);\">Alloy wheels are a popular choice in the automotive industry due to their strength, lightweight properties, and cosmetic appeal. They are made from an alloy of aluminum or magnesium, which provides greater strength and better heat conduction compared to steel wheels. This improved heat conduction aids in dissipating heat from the brakes, which enhances braking performance in demanding driving conditions. Alloy wheels are often purchased for their attractive bare-metal finishes, but these need to be sealed with paint or wheel covers to prevent corrosion.</span></span></p><p style=\"text-align:start\"><span style=\"color:rgb(55, 65, 81);\"><span style=\"background-color:rgba(244, 244, 245, 0.5);\">Alloy wheels offer advantages in terms of handling and fuel efficiency. Lighter wheels can improve handling by reducing unsprung mass, allowing suspension to follow the terrain more closely and thus improve grip. A reduction in overall vehicle mass can also help to reduce fuel consumption. However, not all alloy wheels are lighter than their steel equivalents. Alloy wheels are prone to galvanic corrosion, which can cause tires to leak air if preventive measures are not taken. They are more difficult to repair than steel wheels when bent but are generally more resistant to damage due to their strength.</span></span></p><p style=\"text-align:start\"><span style=\"color:rgb(55, 65, 81);\"><span style=\"background-color:rgba(244, 244, 245, 0.5);\">Alloy wheels are more expensive to produce than standard steel wheels and are often not included as standard equipment. They have become more common since 2000, now being offered on economy and subcompact cars compared to a decade earlier. The high cost of alloy wheels makes them attractive to thieves, and automakers often use locking lug nuts or bolts to deter theft. Most alloy wheels are manufactured using casting, but some are forged, which are usually lighter, stronger, and more expensive than cast wheels. Forged wheels can be one-piece or modular, with the latter consisting of multiple parts held together with bolts.</span></span></p>', 'simple', '1 Item', 500, 20, 19.00, 18.05, 5.00, 0, NULL, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TO09', 0, 'in_stock', 'Alloy Wheel Tyre', 'Alloy wheels are wheels that are made from an alloy of aluminum or magnesium. They generally provide greater strength over pure metals, which are usually much softer and more ductile. Alloys of aluminum or magnesium are typically lighter for the same strength, provide better heat conduction, and often produce improved cosmetic appearance over steel wheels.\n\nThe earliest light-alloy wheels were made of magnesium alloys. Although they lost favor on common vehicles, they remained popular through the 1960s, albeit in very limited numbers. In the mid-to-late 1960s, aluminum-casting refinements allowed the manufacture of safer wheels that were not as brittle. Until this time, most aluminum wheels suffered from low ductility, usually ranging from 2-3% elongation.\n\nLighter wheels can improve handling by reducing unsprung mass, allowing suspension to follow the terrain more closely and thus improve grip. Reduction in overall vehicle mass can also help to reduce fuel consumption. Better heat conduction and a more open wheel design can help dissipate heat from the brakes, which improves braking performance in more demanding driving conditions and reduces the chance of diminished brake performance or even failure due to overheating.\n\nAlloy wheels are also purchased for cosmetic purposes although the cheaper alloys used are usually not corrosion-resistant. Alloys allow the use of attractive bare-metal finishes, but these need to be sealed with paint or wheel covers. Even if so protected the wheels in use will eventually start to corrode after 3 to 5 years but refurbishment is now widely available at a cost. The manufacturing processes also allow intricate, bold designs.', 2137, 2137, NULL, 'Your order is likely to reach you within 4-6 days.', NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 'alloy-wheel-tyre', 1, 25, 1, 1, 'url', 'physical', NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, 0, 'center', 74, NULL, 'fixed', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-29 21:57:19', '2024-05-29 21:57:19');
